The executor service creates and maintains a reusable pool of threads for executing submitted tasks.

Java provides the 4 types of Thread pools
-----------------------------------------

1. Fixed thread pool --  LinkedBlockingQueue -- Threads are limited but task are not limited
2. CachedThreadPool  -- synchronousQueue -- Threads are not limited/unbounded - as soon as task arrive to queue it get empty queue and assign a thread
3. ScheduledThreadPool -- DelayedWorkQueue special queue that deals with schedule/time delays
4. SingleThreadedExecutor -- LinkedBlockingQueue

1. Fixed thread pool
  To be created using Executors.newFixedThreadPool(4);

2. CachedThreadPool
  Here you don't have fixed number of thread and you don't have queue to hold the number of task. Instead queue is replaced by
  something called Synchronous queue. which has space to have only one task. Every time you submit a particular task, it will hold the
  task at the queue location and it will search for any of the thread which are already created and which are free to operate or execute
  the task.if no such thread is available then it will create the new thread it will add to the pool to execute the task.
  so, now you imagine you have 100 task then it will create the 100 thread if all thread all busy. it has also an ability to kill those
  thread which ideal for 60 seconds. so that's when slowly thread pool size will start shrinking.
  Code for this as below
  ExecutorService service = Executor.newCachedThreadPool();

3. ScheduledThreadPool
   Here specifically for the task you want to scheduled after a certain delay.Let say you want to perform some checks such as
   security checks or logging checks or some other kind of checks after every 10 sec.
   you have three method
   1. Service.schedule -- Task to execute at certain delay (Task to run after 10 seconds delay)
   2. Service.scheduleAtFixedRate -- Task which can keep triggering at every 10 secs.
   3. Service.scheduleAtFixedDelay -- It will complete the task say it takes 15 sec after that it will wait for 10 sec
   then schedule instance of the task.(or task to run repeatedly 10 seconds after previous task completes)

4. SingleThreadedExecutor
   it exactly same as fixedThreadPool executor but in this case it has only one pool size. Only one thread fetching the task from
   blocking queue and running it. even if thread gets killed due some exception or so then it will recreates the thread to execute
   the next task.
   This thread pool will useful when you want ensure the task1 executes before task2 or want to maintain some kind of order then
   it will useful.So the task will run sequentially.

Difference between newSingleThreadExecutor and newFixedThreadPool(1):
You can not change thread pool size of executors returned by newSingleThreadExecutor but you can change thread pool size of
executors returned by newFixedThreadPool(1) by calling setCorePoolSize() of the class ThreadPoolExecutor.

Callable and Futures
-------------------
What if task want to return something. There is no way that i can return something from the existing run() method.
So, there is Interface called callable which is created exactly for this purpose.So instead of Runnable
we can implement callable.
 static class Task implements Callable<Integer>{ that what type of value you are going to return
        @Override
        public Integer call(){
          return new Random().nextInt();
        }
 }

Future is nothing but a placeholder for the value which will arrive in sometime in the future. How much in time you can never be sure.
that completely based on the how time call() method takes.
As soon as we submit the callable task the thread pool gives a placeholder which doesn't contain any value. After some point of time
which completely based on how you call method implemented , once result is ready with the thread pool it will update the same
placeholder which it gave you with actual value. Now, when this callable method is being run if your main method calls the f.get()
which is blocking method. Main thread immediately goes into blocked state. because at this point thread pool has not completed the
method and not ready with result yet.That is why main thread goes into blocked state.and once thread sets the value of the placeholder
that is when call is completed. Then the main thread which was blocked goes in to runnable state and can be run subsequently
run by the JVM.

Consider case when you submit the callable task in loop then it can block the main thread even though future return for some other
index but main thread wait until it doesn't return thr value for first index.
Hence, we can overcome with some timeout scenario.
Future has some get overloaded method which has time out facility.
future.get(timeout:1,TimeUnit.SECONDS);
or
you can cancel the task
future.cancel()//make sure you do before the task execution other it will do anything
future.isCancelled() // Return true if task was cancelled
future.isDone()//Return true if task is completed

